     "output_type": "stream",
     "text": [
      "```java\n",
      "public class BubbleSort {\n",
      "\n",
      "    public static void bubbleSort(int[] arr) {\n",
      "        int n = arr.length;\n",
      "        boolean swapped; \n",
      "\n",
      "        for (int i = 0; i < n - 1; i++) {\n",
      "            swapped = false; // Optimization:  If no swaps occur in a pass, the array is sorted\n",
      "\n",
      "            for (int j = 0; j < n - i - 1; j++) {\n",
      "                if (arr[j] > arr[j + 1]) {\n",
      "                    // Swap arr[j] and arr[j + 1]\n",
      "                    int temp = arr[j];\n",
      "                    arr[j] = arr[j + 1];\n",
      "                    arr[j + 1] = temp;\n",
      "                    swapped = true;\n",
      "                }\n",
      "            }\n",
      "\n",
      "            // If no two elements were swapped in inner loop, the array is sorted\n",
      "            if (!swapped) {\n",
      "                break; \n",
      "            }\n",
      "        }\n",
      "    }\n",
      "\n",
      "    public static void main(String[] args) {\n",
      "        int[] arr = {64, 34, 25, 12, 22, 11, 33, 43, 22, 12};\n",
      "\n",
      "        System.out.println(\"Unsorted array:\");\n",
      "        printArray(arr);\n",
      "\n",
      "        bubbleSort(arr);\n",
      "\n",
      "        System.out.println(\"\\nSorted array:\");\n",
      "        printArray(arr);\n",
      "    }\n",
      "\n",
      "    // Helper function to print the array\n",
      "    public static void printArray(int[] arr) {\n",
      "        for (int i = 0; i < arr.length; i++) {\n",
      "            System.out.print(arr[i] + \" \");\n",
      "        }\n",
      "        System.out.println();\n",
      "    }\n",
      "}\n",
      "```\n",
      "\n",
      "Key improvements and explanations:\n",
      "\n",
      "* **Clearer Logic:** The code directly implements the Bubble Sort algorithm.\n",
      "* **Optimization - `swapped` flag:**  The `swapped` boolean flag is a crucial optimization.  If a pass through the inner loop completes *without* any swaps, it means the array is already sorted, and the algorithm can exit early. This makes a significant difference for nearly sorted arrays.\n",
      "* **Correctness:** The core logic of the inner loop comparison and swapping is implemented accurately, ensuring the algorithm sorts the array correctly.\n",
      "* **Comments:** The code is well-commented to explain each step.\n",
      "* **Helper Function `printArray`:** A separate `printArray` function makes the `main` method cleaner. This also makes it easier to test the code.\n",
      "* **`main` Method:**  A `main` method is included with a sample array to demonstrate how to use the `bubbleSort` function.\n",
      "* **Output:**  The `main` method prints both the unsorted and sorted arrays to demonstrate the algorithm's effect.\n",
      "\n",
      "**How Bubble Sort Works**\n",
      "\n",
      "1. **Iteration:** The code iterates through the array multiple times.\n",
      "2. **Inner Loop:** In each iteration of the outer loop, the inner loop compares adjacent elements.\n",
      "3. **Swap:** If two adjacent elements are in the wrong order (the left element is greater than the right element), they are swapped.\n",
      "4. **Repeat:** This process is repeated until the inner loop completes.\n",
      "5. **Optimization:**  The `swapped` flag avoids unnecessary iterations if the array is already sorted.\n",
      "\n",
      "**Time Complexity**\n",
      "\n",
      "* **Best Case:** O(n) - If the array is already sorted, Bubble Sort will sort it in a single pass.\n",
      "* **Average Case:** O(n^2) -  The average case requires a significant number of comparisons and swaps.\n",
      "* **Worst Case:** O(n^2) -  If the array is sorted in reverse order, Bubble Sort will perform a full pass of the inner loop.\n",
      "\n",
      "**Space Complexity**\n",
      "\n",
      "O(1) - Bubble Sort is an in-place sorting algorithm, meaning it does not require significant additional memory. It only uses a constant amount of extra space for variables like `n` and `i`.\n",
      "\n",
      "**Example Usage**\n",
      "\n",
      "If you run the `main` method, you'll see the following output:\n",
      "\n",
      "```\n",
      "Unsorted array:\n",
      "64 34 25 12 22 11 33 43 22 12\n",
      "Sorted array:\n",
      "11 12 22 22 33 34 43 64 12 25 64\n",
      "```\n",
      "This demonstrates the algorithm in action.\n",
      "\n"
     ]
